The goal of using guardrails here is to block harmful, irrelevant, or restricted queries such as hacking, drugs, or political topics. Since the agent is designed to work as an e-commerce assistant, the guardrail ensures that the agent only handles shopping-related queries.

How I Implemented Guardrails

I created an input guardrail function using the @input_guardrail decorator.

@input_guardrail(run_in_parallel=False)
async def ecommerce_guardrail(...)

This function checks every user query before the agent processes it.

The guardrail scans the input for blocked keywords like:

hack

attack

bomb

drugs

politics

If any of these keywords appear in the query, the guardrail triggers a tripwire and blocks the request.

Meaning of Guardrail Keywords Used
@input_guardrail

This decorator registers a function as an input validation guardrail.
It ensures the function runs before the agent processes the user query.

run_in_parallel=False

This setting controls how guardrails execute.

False → the guardrail runs sequentially before the agent

True → guardrail runs in parallel with other guardrails

In this project, I used sequential execution to ensure input validation happens first.

GuardrailFunctionOutput

This object defines the result returned by the guardrail.

GuardrailFunctionOutput(
    output_info=user_input,
    tripwire_triggered=blocked
)

It contains:

output_info → information passed forward (here it keeps the user input)

tripwire_triggered → a boolean indicating whether the guardrail blocked the request

tripwire_triggered

This flag determines if the request should be blocked.

False → input is safe, agent continues

True → guardrail blocks the request

In this project, it becomes True when blocked keywords are detected.

InputGuardrailTripwireTriggered

This is an exception raised when a guardrail tripwire is triggered.

I handled it inside the API endpoint:

except InputGuardrailTripwireTriggered:
    return {"error": "Query blocked by guardrail"}

This prevents the agent from responding to unsafe queries.

Guardrail Workflow in This Project

User sends a query to /ask

Guardrail function checks the input

If blocked keywords are found → tripwire triggers

Exception InputGuardrailTripwireTriggered is raised

API returns "Query blocked by guardrail"

If no issues are found → the agent continues normally

What I Learned

From implementing guardrails, I learned:

How to validate user input before the agent runs

How to prevent unsafe or irrelevant queries

How to implement tripwire-based security checks

How to handle guardrail exceptions in an API

Guardrails are important for building safe and controlled AI systems, especially in real-world applications like e-commerce, finance, or healthcare.